  <h1>Blakeslee Commercial Dishwasher Repair — Los Angeles &amp; Southern California</h1>

  <p>George S. Blakeslee built the first mechanical commercial dishwasher in North America in 1880 — which means by the time Hobart was incorporated and Jackson shipped its first machine, Blakeslee had already been in this business for decades. The company is still at it, now out of Waynesboro, Georgia, building high-volume warewashing equipment for the institutional segment: hotel banquet operations, university dining systems, stadium food service, and large cafeteria operations where throughput is measured in thousands of pieces per hour rather than racks per service.</p>

  <p>In the SoCal market, Blakeslee equipment shows up at the volume end of the spectrum — the UCLA and USC dining systems that run through more racks in a lunch service than most restaurants see in a week, hotel dishrooms along the Wilshire corridor, large venue food service operations from the Forum to SoFi Stadium's concession prep kitchens. When one of these machines goes down, the volume it was handling has to go somewhere — and it can't. That's the call we get. $120 commercial diagnostic applied to the repair. Same-day response throughout SoCal. Call <strong>{phone}</strong>.</p>

  <h2>Blakeslee Equipment We Service</h2>

  <h3>QX PRO — Conveyor Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>Blakeslee's QX PRO is their current flagship conveyor machine — a flight-type and rack-conveyor platform designed for operations where continuous throughput is the operational requirement. The QX PRO is configurable: operators can specify a Heat Recovery System that captures exhaust heat to pre-warm incoming water, a Blower &amp; Dryer unit for air-dry finishing, or both. These add-on systems extend the machine's footprint and introduce additional maintenance points that standard conveyor service doesn't cover.</p>
  <p>The Heat Recovery System on the QX PRO functions the same way as on Meiko's M-iQ and Winterhalter's energy recovery systems: a heat exchanger through which exhaust air passes, recovering thermal energy before the air exits. In LA hard water, the exchanger develops scale deposits that reduce heat recovery efficiency over time — energy consumption rises before any other symptom appears. We check and descale the Heat Recovery System exchanger on every QX PRO visit in the SoCal market as part of the standard service call, not as an optional add-on.</p>
  <p>Conveyor drive failures on the QX PRO follow the same pattern as any high-volume commercial conveyor: drive chain tension requires periodic adjustment in continuous-use operations, zone curtains between wash sections wear and develop tears that allow wash water cross-contamination, and the output-end table limit switch sees high cycle counts from heavy-use operators loading faster than the machine processes. We stock conveyor drive components and curtains for the QX PRO from our commercial parts network.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> QX PRO (standard), QX PRO with Heat Recovery System, QX PRO with Blower &amp; Dryer</p>

  <h3>Rack-Type Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>Blakeslee's rack-type machines are their door-type and passthrough series — the mid-volume workhorse for operations that need more throughput than an undercounter but don't need a full conveyor line. These are in hotel satellite kitchens, catering prep facilities, and mid-size institutional operations throughout the region. The rack-type series uses Blakeslee's Perfecta-Rinse technology — a final rinse system engineered to deliver effective sanitization using less than one gallon of water per cycle. In LA, where commercial water rates are a real operational consideration, this water efficiency matters to operators watching their monthly utility bills.</p>
  <p>The Perfecta-Rinse system's spray nozzle geometry is specific to Blakeslee's engineering — the nozzle pattern is optimized for the reduced water volume. When nozzles scale from LA hard water and the spray pattern degrades, the Perfecta-Rinse system's efficiency advantage disappears before any other symptom is obvious. Spray nozzle condition is the first thing we inspect on any Blakeslee rack-type machine where wash quality has gradually declined.</p>

  <h3>Undercounter &amp; Glasswashers</h3>
  <p>Blakeslee's undercounter dishwashers and glasswashers are found in bar service, hotel room service stations, and smaller food service operations that want the brand reliability of a 140-year-old manufacturer in a compact footprint. These machines use the same Perfecta-Rinse technology as the rack-type series — sub-gallon water consumption per cycle. The undercounter glasswashers are particularly common in hotel bars and event venue bar stations where glass clarity and throughput matter.</p>
  <p>On undercounter Blakeslee machines, the door safety switch and booster heater element are the two most common service calls in the SoCal market — same failure modes as on CMA, Champion, and Jackson undercounters. High door cycle count wears the interlock switch. LA hard water scales the booster element. Neither failure requires major mechanical work; both benefit from the diagnostic step of checking scale before assuming component failure.</p>

  <h2>Blakeslee in the LA Institutional Market</h2>

  <p>Blakeslee's installed base in SoCal skews institutional — the segment where buying decisions happen through food service equipment dealers and facility managers rather than restaurant owners. UCLA Housing &amp; Hospitality, the USC residential dining program, the Los Angeles Convention Center, Staples Center (now Crypto.com Arena) food service operations — this is the Blakeslee market in LA. It's also a market where the person calling for service is often a facilities manager or executive chef rather than an owner-operator, and where PM contracts and documentation matter.</p>

  <p>We structure Blakeslee institutional service accordingly: service documentation for facilities management records, equipment performance baselines established at the first visit, and recommended PM intervals calibrated for LA water conditions rather than the national-average assumptions in Blakeslee's standard maintenance guidance. For a QX PRO running a UCLA dining hall — easily 300+ racks per lunch service — the maintenance interval appropriate for a restaurant doing 80 racks a day simply doesn't apply.</p>

  <h2>Recent Blakeslee Service Calls</h2>

  <h3>"QX PRO conveyor — heat recovery efficiency down, energy bills up, hotel banquet kitchen Century City"</h3>
  <p>Hotel facilities manager called — they'd noticed a steady increase in the dishroom's energy consumption over 8 months, no obvious cause. QX PRO conveyor with the Heat Recovery System installed. Machine was running correctly in every other respect — temperatures normal, throughput fine, no error conditions. Found the Heat Recovery System's heat exchanger passages scaling from continuous operation in LA water without descaling. The exchanger was recovering about 55% of its rated heat transfer due to the scale insulation — the wash heaters were compensating by running longer. Full exchanger descale, re-verified energy recovery performance. Set the hotel on semi-annual Heat Recovery System maintenance — they'd assumed the system was maintenance-free because it had no moving parts. It has no moving parts, but it has heat exchanger passages, and those scale.</p>

  <h3>"Rack-type dishwasher — Perfecta-Rinse spray quality degraded, catering facility Culver City"</h3>
  <p>Catering operation, Blakeslee rack-type machine, chef noticed sanitizer test strips were passing but dish rinse quality was visually inconsistent — some racks coming out cleaner than others. Inconsistent results from a machine that passes sanitizer testing usually points to spray coverage, not temperature or chemistry. Found the Perfecta-Rinse nozzles on the upper spray arm partially blocked — two of the six nozzles were at about 40% of spec flow due to mineral scale. The reduced flow from those nozzles was leaving coverage gaps on upper-rack items. Cleaned and flow-tested all nozzles, verified uniform spray coverage with test racks. Added nozzle inspection to the facility's monthly cleaning checklist.</p>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <p><strong>What is Perfecta-Rinse technology?</strong><br>
  Perfecta-Rinse is Blakeslee's final rinse system engineered to achieve NSF-compliant 180°F sanitization using less than one gallon of water per cycle — significantly below most commercial dishwashers' water consumption. The system relies on precise nozzle geometry to deliver effective coverage with reduced volume. In LA's hard water, those nozzles require regular inspection and cleaning to maintain that coverage — a partially scaled nozzle compromises the Perfecta-Rinse advantage before it shows up in sanitizer test results.</p>

  <p><strong>Does the QX PRO Heat Recovery System require maintenance?</strong><br>
  Yes. The Heat Recovery System uses an internal heat exchanger — no moving parts, but heat exchanger passages that scale from mineral deposits in hard water. In LA water at 250–350 ppm TDS, we recommend semi-annual descaling of the exchanger. When it scales, energy recovery efficiency drops and the wash heaters compensate by running longer — you'll see rising energy bills before any other symptom. We descale it as part of every QX PRO service call in the SoCal market.</p>

  <p><strong>Do you service Blakeslee equipment at institutional accounts?</strong><br>
  Yes — university dining, hotel banquet, venue food service, and large cafeteria operations are a regular part of our commercial work. We provide service documentation appropriate for facilities management records and structure PM recommendations for the actual volume and water conditions of the specific account, not generic maintenance schedules.</p>

  <p><strong>Do you carry Blakeslee OEM parts?</strong><br>
  Yes — conveyor drive components, Perfecta-Rinse spray nozzle assemblies, door safety switches, booster elements, zone curtains, and control components for QX PRO and rack-type series. Non-standard parts for older Blakeslee models are available with 1–2 day sourcing.</p>

  <p><strong>What is your diagnostic fee?</strong><br>
  $120 commercial diagnostic, applied to the repair when you proceed. On-site quote — what we quote is what's on the invoice.</p>

